    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-04-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-04-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="806"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d806">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">684A.86/4–2154</note>
                <head>No. 806<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Secretary of State</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d806fn1">Addressed to Assistant Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_BHA1">Byroade</persName>; signed for the Secretary by John
                        W. Hanes, Jr.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>?,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1954-04-21">April 21,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum Of Conference With President <persName
                            corresp="#p_EGAD1">Eisenhower</persName>, Augusta, <gloss
                            target="#t_GA1">Ga</gloss>., April 19, 1954</hi>
                </p>
                <p>We discussed the Arab-Israeli tension and the matter of military aid to Iraq. I
                    gave the President our State Department estimate of the present situation, and
                    the danger that the Israeli might be deliberately trying to break the armistice
                    open on the theory that that was the only way to get a better arrangement. I
                    also referred to the Arab fear of increased Jewish immigration and consequent
                    inevitable expansion. The President agreed that we should continue our present
                    policy of impartiality and should not be deterred by political pressures which
                    might generate in connection with the forthcoming elections. He suggested I
                    should make a speech on this subject when I returned, a speech which he would go
                    over with me in advance. He felt it was all right to conclude the mutual
                    security <pb facs="1569" n="1529" xml:id="pg_1529"/> agreement with Iraq on the
                    condition that the actual aid given should be dependent upon the international
                    situation at the time. He hoped very much that the agreement would in fact lead
                    to identification of agreement with Turkey–Pakistan. I said that I thought the
                    best hope of this was to proceed as we had planned, but I was confident that our
                    action would be met by strong political opposition from elements subject to
                    Zionist influence.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JFD</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
